  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Determine who will administer the tools, especially the asset repository. There are several kinds of administrative&#xD;
    skills required to support asset repositories. In general, someone needs to configure the environment for the&#xD;
    repository services, whereas someone needs to configure the integrations with other repositories, and someone needs to&#xD;
    configure the information model for the assets, such as asset types, classification schemas, and so forth.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The selected topology impacts the configuration effort and the overall cost of ownership.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A key part of this step is to determine the appropriate topology to meet the needs of the enterprise. In general a&#xD;
    centralized asset repository database manages the asset and repository metadata. The asset use and manipulation can be&#xD;
    distributed to remote sites while leaving asset repository servers at the central site.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The asset repository should be architected to support many topology configurations.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
